===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} ''[[tun|tūn]]'' 'enclosure, village', from {{proto|Germanic|tunaz||tunan}} 'fence' (cf. Dutch ''[[tuin]]'' ‘garden’, German ''[[Zaun]]'', Danish/Swedish ''[[tun]]''), from Gaulish ''dunon'' 'hill; hillfort' (compare Welsh {{term|din||hill|lang=cy}}, Irish {{term|dún||fortress|lang=ga}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|dheuh₂||dhuh₂}} 'to finish, come full circle' (compare Hittite ''tuhhušta'' 'it is finished', Latin {{term|funus|fūnus|burial|lang=la}}, Ancient Greek {{term|θνητός|tr=thnētos||mortal|lang=grc}}, {{term|θάνατος|tr=thanatos||death|lang=grc}}, ''thaneīn'' 'to die', Sanskrit ''ádhvanīt'' 'he vanished').

